SIMPLE: subtraction
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Subtraction
<hw>Sub*trac"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>subtractio</ets> a drawing back. See <er>Subtract</er>, and cf.
<er>Substraction</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or operation of
subtracting or taking away a part.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>The taking of a lesser number or
quantity from a greater of the same kind or denomination; an operation
for finding the difference between two numbers or quantities.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>The withdrawing or withholding from
a person of some right to which he is entitled by law.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Thus the <xex>subtraction</xex> of conjugal rights is
when either the husband or wife withdraws from the other and lives
separate without sufficient reason. The <xex>subtraction</xex> of a
legacy is the withholding or detailing of it from the legatee by the
executor. In like manner, the withholding of any service, rent, duty, or
custom, is a <xex>subtraction</xex>, for which the law gives a
remedy.</note> <rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Subtractive</ent>⟦br⟧
